# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: d-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D is not source-compatible with C and C++ source code in general.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] However, any code that is legal in both C/C++ and D should behave in the same way.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Like C++, D has closures, anonymous functions, compile-time function execution, design by contract, ranges, built-in container iteration concepts, and type inference.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D's declaration, statement and expression syntaxes also closely match those of C++.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Unlike C++, D also implements garbage collection, first-class arrays (`std::array` in C++ are technically not first-class), array slicing, nested functions and lazy evaluation.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D uses Java-style single inheritance with interfaces and mixins rather than C++-style multiple inheritance.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Like C++, and unlike application languages such as Java and C#, D supports low-level programming, including inline assembler.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Inline assembler allows programmers to enter machine-specific assembly code within standard D code.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] System programmers use this method to access the low-level features of the processor that are needed to run programs that interface directly with the underlying hardware, such as operating systems and device drivers.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Low-level programming is also used to write higher performance code than would be produced by a compiler.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D supports function overloading and operator overloading.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Symbols (functions, variables, classes) can be declared in any order; forward declarations are not needed.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] In D, text character strings are arrays of characters, and arrays in D are bounds-checked.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D has first-class types for complex and imaginary numbers.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Imperative programming in D is almost identical to that in C.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Functions, data, statements, declarations and expressions work just as they do in C, and the C runtime library may be accessed directly.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] However, unlike C, D's `foreach` loop construct allows looping over a collection.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D also allows nested functions, which are functions that are declared inside another function, and which may access the enclosing function's local variables.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Object-oriented programming in D is based on a single inheritance hierarchy, with all classes derived from class Object.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D does not support multiple inheritance; instead, it uses Java-style interfaces, which are comparable to C++'s pure abstract classes, and mixins, which separate common functionality from the inheritance hierarchy.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D also allows the defining of static and final (non-virtual) methods in interfaces.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Interfaces and inheritance in D support covariant types for return types of overridden methods.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D supports type forwarding and optional custom dynamic dispatch.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Classes (and interfaces) in D can contain invariants which are automatically checked before and after entry to public methods, in accord with the design by contract methodology.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Many aspects of classes (and structs) can be introspected automatically at compile time (a form of reflective programming (reflection) using `type traits`) and at runtime (RTTI / `TypeInfo`), to facilitate generic code or automatic code generation (usually using compile-time techniques).
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D supports functional programming features such as function literals, closures, recursively-immutable objects and the use of higher-order functions.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] There are two built-in types for function literals, `function`, which is simply a pointer to a stack-allocated function, and `delegate`, which also includes a pointer to the relevant stack frame, the surrounding ‘environment’, which contains the current local variables.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Type inference may be used with an anonymous function, in which case the compiler creates a `delegate` unless it can prove that an environment pointer is not necessary.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Likewise, to implement a closure, the compiler places enclosed local variables on the heap only if necessary (for example, if a closure is returned by another function, and exits that function's scope).
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] When using type inference, the compiler will also add attributes such as `pure` and `nothrow` to a function's type, if it can prove that they apply.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Other functional features such as currying and common higher-order functions such as map, filter, and reduce are available through the standard library modules `std.functional` and `std.algorithm`.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Parallel programming concepts are implemented in the library, and do not require extra support from the compiler.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] However the D type system and compiler ensure that data sharing can be detected and managed transparently.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] `iota(11).parallel` is equivalent to `std.parallelism.parallel(iota(11))` by using UFCS.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The same module also supports `taskPool` which can be used for dynamic creation of parallel tasks, and for map-filter-reduce and fold style operations on ranges (and arrays), which is useful when combined with functional operations.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] `std.algorithm.map` returns a lazily evaluated range rather than an array.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] This way, the elements are computed by each worker task in parallel automatically.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Concurrency is fully implemented in the library, and it does not require support from the compiler.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Alternative implementations and methodologies of writing concurrent code are possible.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The use of D typing system does help ensure memory safety.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Metaprogramming is supported through templates, compile-time function execution, tuples, and string mixins.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The following examples demonstrate some of D's compile-time features.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Templates in D can be written in a more imperative style compared to the C++ functional style for templates.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] In the following two examples, the template and function defined above are used to compute factorials.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] This is an example of compile-time function execution (CTFE).
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] String mixins, combined with compile-time function execution, allow for the generation of D code using string operations at compile time.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Memory is usually managed with garbage collection, but specific objects may be finalized immediately when they go out of scope.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] This is what the majority of programs and libraries written in D use.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Explicit memory management is possible using the overloaded operator new, by calling C's malloc and free directly, or implementing custom allocator schemes such as stack allocation with fallback, RAII-style allocation, reference counting, or shared reference counting.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Garbage collection can be controlled: programmers may add and exclude memory ranges from being observed by the collector, can disable and enable the collector and force either a generational or full collection cycle.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The language documentation provides examples of how to implement alternative memory management schemes for scenarios where garbage collection is not preferred.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] In functions, `struct` instances are by default allocated on the stack, while `class` instances by default allocated on the heap (with only reference to the class instance being on the stack).
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] However this can be changed for classes, for example using standard library template `std.typecons.scoped`, or by using `new` for structs and assigning to a pointer instead of a value-based variable.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] In functions, static arrays (of known size) are allocated on the stack.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] For dynamic arrays, one can use the `core.stdc.stdlib.alloca` function (similar to `alloca` in C), to allocate memory on the stack.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The returned pointer can be used (recast) into a (typed) dynamic array, by means of a slice (however resizing array, including appending must be avoided; and for obvious reasons they must not be returned from the function).
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] A `scope` keyword can be used both to annotate parts of code, but also variables and classes/structs, to indicate they should be destroyed (destructor called) immediately on scope exit.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Whatever the memory is deallocated also depends on implementation and class-vs-struct differences.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] `std.experimental.allocator` contains modular and composable allocator templates to create custom allocators for specific use cases.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] SafeD is the name given to the subset of D that can be guaranteed to be memory safe.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Functions marked `@safe` are checked at compile time to ensure that they do not use any features that could result in corruption of memory, such as pointer arithmetic and unchecked casts.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Any other functions called must also be marked as `@safe` or `@trusted`.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Functions can be marked `@trusted` for the cases where the compiler cannot distinguish between safe use of a feature that is disabled in SafeD and a potential case of memory corruption.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Initially under the banners of DIP1000 and DIP25 (now part of the language specification), D provides protections against certain ill-formed constructions involving the lifetimes of data.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The current mechanisms in place primarily deal with function parameters and stack memory; however, the language design roadmap includes plans to expand lifetime tracking within the D programming language, drawing on concepts from the Rust programming language.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] (influenced by ideas from Rust programming language).
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Within @safe code, the lifetime of an assignment involving a reference type is checked to ensure that the lifetime of the assignee is longer than that of the assigned.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] When applied to function parameter which are either of pointer type or references, the keywords *return* and *scope* constrain the lifetime and use of that parameter.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] C's application binary interface (ABI) is supported, as well as all of C's fundamental and derived types, enabling direct access to existing C code and libraries.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D bindings are available for many popular C libraries.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Additionally, C's standard library is part of standard D.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] On Microsoft Windows, D can access Component Object Model (COM) code.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] As long as memory management is properly performed, many other languages can be mixed with D in a single binary.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] For example, the GDC compiler allows to link and intermix C, C++, and other supported language codes such as Objective-C.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D code (functions) can also be marked as using C, C++, Pascal ABIs, and thus be passed to the libraries written in these languages as callbacks.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Similarly data can be interchanged between the codes written in these languages in both ways.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] This usually restricts use to primitive types, pointers, some forms of arrays, unions, structs, and only some types of function pointers.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Because many other programming languages often provide the C application programming interface (API) for writing extensions or running the interpreter of the languages, D can interface directly with these languages also, using standard C bindings (with a thin D interface file).
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] For example, bi-directional bindings exist for the languages Python, Lua, and others, often using compile-time code generation and compile-time type reflection methods.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] where `namespace` is the name of the C++ namespace.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The D programming language has an official subset known as "Better C".
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] This subset forbids access to D features requiring use of runtime libraries other than that of C.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Walter Bright started working on a new language in 1999.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D was first released in December 2001 and reached version 1.0 in January 2007.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The first version of the language (D1) concentrated on the imperative, object oriented and metaprogramming paradigms, similar to C++.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Some members of the D community created an alternative runtime and standard library named Tango, as an alternative to Phobos, D's official runtime and standard library.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The first public Tango announcement came within days of D 1.0's release.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Tango adopted a different programming style, embracing OOP and high modularity.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Being a community-led project, Tango was more open to contributions, which allowed it to progress faster than the official standard library.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] At that time, Tango and Phobos were incompatible due to different runtime support APIs (the garbage collector, threading support, etc.).
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] This made it impossible to use both libraries in the same project.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The existence of two widely used libraries meant that some packages used Phobos and others used Tango, creating an incompatibility across different projects.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] In June 2007, the first version of D2 was released.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The beginning of D2's development signaled D1's stabilization.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The first version of the language has been placed in maintenance, only receiving corrections and implementation bugfixes.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D2 introduced breaking changes to the language, beginning with its first const system.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D2 later added numerous other language features, such as closures, purity, and support for the functional and concurrent programming paradigms.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D2 also solved standard library problems by separating the runtime from the standard library.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The completion of a D2 Tango port was announced in February 2012.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The release of Andrei Alexandrescu's book *The D Programming Language* on 12 June 2010, marked the stabilization of D2, which today is commonly referred to as just "D".
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] In January 2011, D development moved from a bugtracker / patch-submission basis to GitHub.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] This has led to a significant increase in contributions to the compiler, runtime and standard library.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] In December 2011, Andrei Alexandrescu announced that D1, the first version of the language, would be discontinued on 31 December 2012.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The final D1 release, D v1.076, was on 31 December 2012.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Code for the official D compiler, the *Digital Mars D compiler* by Walter Bright, was originally released under a custom license, qualifying as source available but not conforming to the Open Source Definition.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] In 2014, the compiler front-end was re-licensed as open source under the Boost Software License.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] This re-licensed code excluded the back-end, which had been partially developed at Symantec.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] On 7 April 2017, the whole compiler was made available under the Boost license after Symantec gave permission to re-license the back-end, too.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] On 21 June 2017, the D Language was accepted for inclusion in GCC.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Most current D implementations compile directly into machine code.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Bright said in 2020 "The biggest project is implementing the D compiler itself in 100% D".
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Using above compilers and toolchains, it is possible to compile D programs to target many different architectures, including IA-32, amd64, AArch64, PowerPC, MIPS64, DEC Alpha, Motorola m68k, SPARC, s390, WebAssembly.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The primary supported operating systems are Windows and Linux, but various compilers also support Mac OS X, FreeBSD, NetBSD, AIX, Solaris/OpenSolaris and Android, either as a host or target, or both.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] WebAssembly target (supported via LDC and LLVM) can operate in any WebAssembly environment, like modern web browser (Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Apple Safari), or dedicated Wasm virtual machines.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Editors and integrated development environments (IDEs) supporting syntax highlighting and partial code completion for the language include SlickEdit, Emacs, vim, SciTE, Smultron, Zeus, and Geany among others.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Open source D IDEs for Windows exist, some written in D, such as Poseidon, D-IDE, and Entice Designer.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D applications can be debugged using any C/C++ debugger, like GNU Debugger (GDB) or WinDbg, although support for various D-specific language features is extremely limited.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] On Windows, D programs can be debugged using Ddbg, or Microsoft debugging tools (WinDBG and Visual Studio), after having converted the debug information using cv2pdb.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The ZeroBUGS Archived 23 December 2017 at the Wayback Machine debugger for Linux has experimental support for the D language.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Ddbg can be used with various IDEs or from the command line; ZeroBUGS has its own graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] Notable organisations that use the D programming language for projects include Facebook, eBay, and Netflix.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] D has been successfully used for AAA games, language interpreters, virtual machines, an operating system kernel, GPU programming, web development, numerical analysis, GUI applications, a passenger information system, machine learning, text processing, web and application servers and research.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The North Korean hacking group Lazarus exploited CVE-2021-44228, aka "Log4Shell," to deploy three malware families written in DLang.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The lack of agility in the development process and the difficulty of introducing changes to the D language are described in a blog post article by a former contributor.
[src:d-language/d-programming-language] The apparent frustration described there has led to the *OpenD* fork on January 1, 2024.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Generic programming was introduced to the mainstream with Ada in 1977.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] With templates in C++, generic programming became part of the repertoire of professional library design.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The techniques were further improved and *parameterized types* were introduced in the influential 1994 book *Design Patterns*.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] New techniques were introduced by Andrei Alexandrescu in his 2001 book *Modern C++ Design: Generic Programming and Design Patterns Applied*.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Subsequently, D implemented the same ideas.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Such software entities are known as *generics* in Ada, C#, Delphi, Eiffel, F#, Java, Mojo, Nim, Python, Go, Rust, Swift, TypeScript, and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:d-language/generic-programming] They are known as *parametric polymorphism* in ML, Scala, Julia, and Haskell.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The "generic programming" paradigm is an approach to software decomposition whereby fundamental requirements on types are abstracted from across concrete examples of algorithms and data structures and formalized as concepts, analogously to the abstraction of algebraic theories in abstract algebra.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Early examples of this programming approach were implemented in Scheme and Ada, although the best known example is the Standard Template Library (STL), which developed a theory of iterators that is used to decouple sequence data structures and the algorithms operating on them.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For example, given *N* sequence data structures, e.g. singly linked list, vector etc., and *M* algorithms to operate on them, e.g.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] `find`, `sort` etc., a direct approach would implement each algorithm specifically for each data structure, giving *N* × *M* combinations to implement.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Thus, only *N* + *M* data structure-algorithm combinations need be implemented.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] An important point is that a data structure will return a model of the most general concept that can be implemented efficiently—computational complexity requirements are explicitly part of the concept definition.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This limits the data structures a given algorithm can be applied to and such complexity requirements are a major determinant of data structure choice.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Generic programming similarly has been applied in other domains, e.g. graph algorithms.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Although this approach often uses language features of compile-time genericity and templates, it is independent of particular language-technical details.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] — Alexander Stepanov, An Interview with A.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Other programming paradigms that have been described as generic programming include *Datatype generic programming* as described in "Generic Programming – an Introduction".
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The *Scrap your boilerplate* approach is a lightweight generic programming approach for Haskell.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] In this article we distinguish the high-level programming paradigms of *generic programming*, above, from the lower-level programming language *genericity mechanisms* used to implement them (see Programming language support for genericity).
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For further discussion and comparison of generic programming paradigms, see.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Genericity facilities have existed in high-level languages since at least the 1970s in languages such as ML, CLU and Ada, and were subsequently adopted by many object-based and object-oriented languages, including BETA, C++, D, Eiffel, Java, and DEC's now defunct Trellis-Owl.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Genericity is implemented and supported differently in various programming languages; the term "generic" has also been used differently in various programming contexts.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For example, in Forth the compiler can execute code while compiling and one can create new *compiler keywords* and new implementations for those words on the fly.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] It has few *words* that expose the compiler behaviour and therefore naturally offers *genericity* capacities that, however, are not referred to as such in most Forth texts.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The term has been used in functional programming, specifically in Haskell-like languages, which use a structural type system where types are always parametric and the actual code on those types is generic.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] These uses still serve a similar purpose of code-saving and rendering an abstraction.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Arrays and structs can be viewed as predefined generic types.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Every usage of an array or struct type instantiates a new concrete type, or reuses a previous instantiated type.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Array element types and struct element types are parameterized types, which are used to instantiate the corresponding generic type.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] All this is usually built-in in the compiler and the syntax differs from other generic constructs.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Some extensible programming languages try to unify built-in and user defined generic types.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] A broad survey of genericity mechanisms in programming languages follows.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For a specific survey comparing suitability of mechanisms for generic programming, see.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] When creating container classes in statically typed languages, it is inconvenient to write specific implementations for each datatype contained, especially if the code for each datatype is virtually identical.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Above, `T` is a placeholder for whatever type is specified when the list is created.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] These "generic objects of type `T`", commonly called templates, allow a class to be reused with different datatypes as long as certain contracts such as subtypes and signature are kept.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This genericity mechanism should not be confused with *inclusion polymorphism*, which is the algorithmic usage of exchangeable sub-classes: for instance, a list of objects of type `MovingEntity` containing objects of type `Animal` and `Car`.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The C++ `template` construct used above is widely cited as the genericity construct that popularized the notion among programmers and language designers and supports many generic programming idioms.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The D language also offers fully generic-capable templates based on the C++ precedent but with a simplified syntax.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The Java language has provided genericity facilities syntactically based on C++'s since the introduction of Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE) 5.0.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] C# 2.0, Oxygene 1.5 (formerly Chrome) and Visual Basic (.NET) 2005 have constructs that exploit the support for generics present in Microsoft .NET Framework since version 2.0.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Ada has had generics since it was first designed in 1977–1980.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The standard library uses generics to provide many services.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Ada 2005 adds a comprehensive generic container library to the standard library, which was inspired by C++'s Standard Template Library.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] A *generic unit* is a package or a subprogram that takes one or more *generic formal parameters*.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] A *generic formal parameter* is a value, a variable, a constant, a type, a subprogram, or even an instance of another, designated, generic unit.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For generic formal types, the syntax distinguishes between discrete, floating-point, fixed-point, access (pointer) types, etc.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Some formal parameters can have default values.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] To *instantiate* a generic unit, the programmer passes *actual* parameters for each formal.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The generic instance then behaves just like any other unit.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] It is possible to instantiate generic units at run-time, for example, inside a loop.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The language syntax allows precise specification of constraints on generic formal parameters.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For example, it is possible to specify that a generic formal type will only accept a modular type as the actual.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] In this example, `Array_Type` is constrained by both `Index_Type` and `Element_Type`.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] When instantiating the unit, the programmer must pass an actual array type that satisfies these constraints.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The disadvantage of this fine-grained control is a complicated syntax, but, because all generic formal parameters are completely defined in the specification, the compiler can instantiate generics without looking at the body of the generic.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Unlike C++, Ada does not allow specialised generic instances, and requires that all generics be instantiated explicitly.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] C++ uses templates to enable generic programming techniques.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The C++ Standard Library includes the Standard Template Library or STL that provides a framework of templates for common data structures and algorithms.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Templates in C++ may also be used for template metaprogramming, which is a way of pre-evaluating some of the code at compile-time rather than run-time.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Using template specialization, C++ Templates are Turing complete.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] There are many kinds of templates, the most common being function templates and class templates.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] A *function template* is a pattern for creating ordinary functions based upon the parameterizing types supplied when instantiated.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For example, the C++ Standard Template Library contains the function template `std::max(x, y)` that creates functions that return either `x` or `y`, whichever is larger.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The compiler examines the arguments used to call `max` and determines that this is a call to `max(int, int)`.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This works whether the arguments `x` and `y` are integers, strings, or any other type for which the expression `x < y` is sensible, or more specifically, for any type for which `operator<` is defined.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Common inheritance is not needed for the set of types that can be used, and so it is very similar to duck typing.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] A program defining a custom data type can use operator overloading to define the meaning of `<` for that type, thus allowing its use with the `std::max()` function template.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] While this may seem a minor benefit in this isolated example, in the context of a comprehensive library like the STL it allows the programmer to get extensive functionality for a new data type, just by defining a few operators for it.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Merely defining `<` allows a type to be used with the standard `std::sort()`, `std::stable_sort()`, and `std::binary_search()` algorithms or to be put inside data structures such as `std::set<T>`s (equivalent to `TreeSet<T>`, heaps, and associative arrays.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] C++ templates are completely type safe at compile time.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] As a demonstration, the standard type `std::complex<T>` does not define the `<` operator, because there is no strict order on complex numbers.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Therefore, `std::max(x, y)` will fail with a compile error, if `x` and `y` are `complex` values.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Likewise, other templates that rely on `<` cannot be applied to `complex` data unless a comparison (in the form of a functor or function) is provided.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For instance, `std::complex<T>` cannot be used as key for a `std::map<K, V>` (equivalent to `TreeMap<K, V>`) unless a comparison is provided.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Unfortunately, compilers historically generate somewhat esoteric, long, and unhelpful error messages for this sort of error.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Ensuring that a certain object adheres to a method protocol can alleviate this issue.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Languages which use `std::compare` instead of `<` can also use `std::complex<T>` values as keys.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Another kind of template, a *class template*, extends the same concept to classes.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] A class template specialization is a class.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Class templates are often used to make generic containers.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For example, the STL has a doubly linked list container, `std::list<T>` (equivalent to `LinkedList<T>`).
[src:d-language/generic-programming] To make a linked list of integers, one writes `list<int>`, while a list of strings is denoted `list<string>`.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] A `std::list<T>` has a set of standard functions associated with it, that work for any compatible parameterizing types.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] C++20 introduces constraining template types using concepts.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] A powerful feature of C++'s templates is *template specialization*.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This allows alternative implementations to be provided based on certain characteristics of the parameterized type that is being instantiated.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Template specialization has two purposes: to allow certain forms of optimization, and to reduce code bloat.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For example, consider a `sort()` template function.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] One of the primary activities that such a function does is to swap or exchange the values in two of the container's positions.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] If the values are large (in terms of the number of bytes it takes to store each of them), then it is often quicker to first build a separate list of pointers to the objects, sort those pointers, and then build the final sorted sequence.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] If the values are quite small however it is usually fastest to just swap the values in-place as needed.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Furthermore, if the parameterized type is already of some pointer-type, then there is no need to build a separate pointer array.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Template specialization allows the template creator to write different implementations and to specify the characteristics that the parameterized type(s) must have for each implementation to be used.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Unlike function templates, class templates can be partially specialized.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] That means that an alternate version of the class template code can be provided when some of the template parameters are known, while leaving other template parameters generic.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This can be used, for example, to create a default implementation (the *primary specialization*) that assumes that copying a parameterizing type is expensive and then create partial specializations for types that are cheap to copy, thus increasing overall efficiency.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Clients of such a class template just use specializations of it without needing to know whether the compiler used the primary specialization or some partial specialization in each case.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Class templates can also be *fully specialized,* which means that an alternate implementation can be provided when all of the parameterizing types are known.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Some uses of templates, such as the `max()` function, were formerly filled by function-like preprocessor macros (a legacy of the C language).
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Macros are expanded (copy pasted) by the preprocessor, before program compiling; templates are actual real functions.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Macros are always expanded inline; templates can also be inline functions when the compiler deems it appropriate.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] However, templates are generally considered an improvement over macros for these purposes.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Templates avoid some of the common errors found in code that makes heavy use of function-like macros, such as evaluating parameters with side effects twice.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Perhaps most importantly, templates were designed to be applicable to much larger problems than macros.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Many compilers historically had poor support for templates, thus the use of templates could make code somewhat less portable.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Support may also be poor when a C++ compiler is being used with a linker that is not C++-aware, or when attempting to use templates across shared library boundaries.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Compilers can produce confusing, long, and sometimes unhelpful error messages when errors are detected in code that uses SFINAE.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This can make templates difficult to develop with.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Finally, the use of templates requires the compiler to generate a separate *instance* of the templated class or function for every type parameters used with it.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] (This is necessary because types in C++ are not all the same size, and the sizes of data fields are important to how classes work.) So the indiscriminate use of templates can lead to code bloat, resulting in excessively large executables.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] However, judicious use of template specialization and derivation can dramatically reduce such code bloat in some cases:So, can derivation be used to reduce the problem of code replicated because templates are used?
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This would involve deriving a template from an ordinary class.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This technique proved successful in curbing code bloat in real use.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Templated classes or functions may require an *explicit specialization* of the template class which would require rewriting of an entire class for a specific template parameters used by it.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The extra instantiations generated by templates can also cause some debuggers to have difficulty working gracefully with templates.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For example, setting a debug breakpoint within a template from a source file may either miss setting the breakpoint in the actual instantiation desired or may set a breakpoint in every place the template is instantiated.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Also, the implementation source code for the template must be completely available (e.g. included in a header) to the translation unit (source file) using it.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Templates, including much of the Standard Library, if not included in header files, cannot be compiled.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] (This is in contrast to non-templated code, which may be compiled to binary, providing only a declarations header file for code using it.) This may be a disadvantage by exposing the implementing code, which removes some abstractions, and could restrict its use in closed-source projects.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The D language supports templates based in design on C++.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Templates in D use a different syntax than in C++: whereas in C++ template parameters are wrapped in angular brackets (`Template<param1, param2>`), D uses an exclamation sign and parentheses: `Template!(param1, param2)`.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This avoids the C++ parsing difficulties due to ambiguity with comparison operators.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] If there is only one parameter, the parentheses can be omitted.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Conventionally, D combines the above features to provide compile-time polymorphism using trait-based generic programming.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Combining the above allows generating code based on existing declarations.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For example, D serialization frameworks can enumerate a type's members and generate specialized functions for each serialized type to perform serialization and deserialization.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] User-defined attributes could further indicate serialization rules.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The `import` expression and compile-time function execution also allow efficiently implementing domain-specific languages.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Generic classes have been a part of Eiffel since the original method and language design.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The foundation publications of Eiffel, use the term *genericity* to describe creating and using generic classes.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Generic classes are declared with their class name and a list of one or more *formal generic parameters*.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The formal generic parameters are placeholders for arbitrary class names that will be supplied when a declaration of the generic class is made, as shown in the two *generic derivations* below, where `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are other class names.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are considered *actual generic parameters* as they provide real class names to substitute for `G` in actual use.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Within the Eiffel type system, although class `LIST [G]` is considered a class, it is not considered a type.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] However, a generic derivation of `LIST [G]` such as `LIST [ACCOUNT]` is considered a type.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For the list class shown above, an actual generic parameter substituting for `G` can be any other available class.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] To constrain the set of classes from which valid actual generic parameters can be chosen, a *generic constraint* can be specified.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] In the declaration of class `SORTED_LIST` below, the generic constraint dictates that any valid actual generic parameter will be a class that inherits from class `COMPARABLE`.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The generic constraint ensures that elements of a `SORTED_LIST` can in fact be sorted.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Support for the *generics*, or "containers-of-type-T" was added to the Java programming language in 2004 as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] In Java, generics are only checked at compile time for type correctness.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The generic type information is then removed via a process called type erasure, to maintain compatibility with old JVM implementations, making it unavailable at runtime.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For example, a `List<String>` is converted to the raw type `java.util.List`.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The compiler inserts type casts to convert the elements to the `java.lang.String` type when they are retrieved from the list, reducing performance compared to other implementations such as C++ templates.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Generics were added as part of .NET Framework 2.0 in November 2005, based on a research prototype from Microsoft Research started in 1999.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Although similar to generics in Java, .NET generics do not apply type erasure, but implement generics as a first class mechanism in the runtime using reification.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This design choice provides additional functionality, such as allowing reflection with preservation of generic types, and alleviating some of the limits of erasure (such as being unable to create generic arrays).
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This also means that there is no performance hit from runtime casts and normally expensive boxing conversions.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] When primitive and value types are used as generic arguments, they get specialized implementations, allowing for efficient generic collections and methods.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] As in C++ and Java, nested generic types such as `Dictionary<string, List<int>>` are valid types, however are advised against for member signatures in code analysis design rules.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] .NET allows six varieties of generic type constraints using the `where` keyword including restricting generic types to be value types, to be classes, to have constructors, and to implement interfaces.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The `MakeAtLeast()` method allows operation on arrays, with elements of generic type `T`.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The method's type constraint indicates that the method is applicable to any type `T` that implements the generic `System.IComparable<T>` interface.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This ensures a compile time error, if the method is called if the type does not support comparison.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The interface provides the generic method `CompareTo(T)`.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The above method could also be written without generic types, simply using the non-generic `System.Array` type.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] However, since arrays are contravariant, the casting would not be type safe, and the compiler would be unable to find certain possible errors that would otherwise be caught when using generic types.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] In addition, the method would need to access the array items as `object`s instead, and would require casting to compare two elements.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] A notable behavior of static members in a generic .NET class is static member instantiation per run-time type (see example below).
[src:d-language/generic-programming] For Pascal, generics were first implemented in 2006, in the implementation Free Pascal.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The Object Pascal dialect Delphi acquired generics in the 2007 Delphi 11 release by CodeGear, initially only with the .NET compiler (since discontinued) before being added to the native code in the 2009 Delphi 12 release.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The semantics and abilities of Delphi generics are largely modelled on those of generics in .NET 2.0, though the implementation is by necessity quite different.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] As with C#, methods and whole types can have one or more type parameters.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] In the example, TArray is a generic type (defined by the language) and MakeAtLeast a generic method.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The available constraints are very similar to the available constraints in C#: any value type, any class, a specific class or interface, and a class with a parameterless constructor.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Multiple constraints act as an additive union.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Free Pascal implemented generics in 2006 in version 2.2.0, before Delphi and with different syntax and semantics.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] However, since FPC version 2.6.0, the Delphi-style syntax is available when using the language mode `{$mode Delphi}`.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Thus, Free Pascal code supports generics in either style.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The type class mechanism of Haskell supports generic programming.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] All the necessary methods will be "derived" – that is, constructed automatically – based on the structure of the type.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] This results in an equality function (`==`) and a string representation function (`show`) being automatically defined for any type of the form `BinTree T` provided that `T` itself supports those operations.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Ralf Hinze (2004) has shown that a similar effect can be achieved for user-defined type classes by certain programming techniques.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Other researchers have proposed approaches to this and other kinds of genericity in the context of Haskell and extensions to Haskell (discussed below).
[src:d-language/generic-programming] PolyP was the first generic programming language extension to Haskell.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] In PolyP, generic functions are called *polytypic*.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The language introduces a special construct in which such polytypic functions can be defined via structural induction over the structure of the pattern functor of a regular datatype.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Regular datatypes in PolyP are a subset of Haskell datatypes.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] A regular datatype t must be of kind ** → **, and if *a* is the formal type argument in the definition, then all recursive calls to *t* must have the form *t a*.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] These restrictions rule out higher-kinded datatypes and nested datatypes, where the recursive calls are of a different form.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Generic Haskell is another extension to Haskell, developed at Utrecht University in the Netherlands.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] The resulting type-indexed value can be specialized to any type.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Clean offers generic programming based PolyP and the Generic Haskell as supported by the GHC ≥ 6.0.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] It parametrizes by kind as those but offers overloading.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Languages in the ML family support generic programming through parametric polymorphism and generic modules called *functors.* Both Standard ML and OCaml provide functors, which are similar to class templates and to Ada's generic packages.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Scheme syntactic abstractions also have a connection to genericity – these are in fact a superset of C++ templates.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] A Verilog module may take one or more parameters, to which their actual values are assigned upon the instantiation of the module.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] One example is a generic register array where the array width is given via a parameter.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Such an array, combined with a generic wire vector, can make a generic buffer or memory module with an arbitrary bit width out of a single module implementation.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] VHDL, being derived from Ada, also has generic abilities.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] C has a feature called "type-generic expressions" using the `_Generic` keyword: This feature gives C function overloading capabilities, but is not related to generic programming.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Generic programming can be achieved by using the preprocessor to define the generic code, with macro expansion taking the role of *instantiation*.
[src:d-language/generic-programming] Sometimes, the non-standard extension "statement expressions" is used to simulate function-like behaviour for generic code.
[src:d-language/spec-spec] If you spot a problem with this page, click here to create a GitHub issue.
[src:d-language/spec-spec] Quickly fork, edit online, and submit a pull request for this page.
[src:d-language/spec-spec] If you'd like to make larger changes you may want to consider using a local clone.
[src:d-language/spec-spec] This is the specification for the D Programming Language.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] Systems programming requires a great degree of hardware awareness.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] Its goal is to achieve efficient use of available resources, either because the software itself is performance-critical or because even small efficiency improvements directly transform into significant savings of time or money.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] In systems programming, often limited programming facilities are available.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] The use of automatic garbage collection is not common and debugging is sometimes hard to do.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] The runtime library, if available at all, is usually far less powerful, and does less error checking.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] Because of those limitations, monitoring and logging are often used; operating systems may have extremely elaborate logging subsystems.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] Implementing certain parts in operating systems and networking requires systems programming, for example implementing paging (virtual memory) or a device driver for an operating system.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] Originally systems programmers invariably wrote in assembly language.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] Experiments with hardware support in high level languages in the late 1960s led to such languages as PL/S, BLISS, BCPL, and extended ALGOL for Burroughs Large Systems.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] Forth also has applications as a systems language.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] In the 1970s, C became widespread, aided by the growth of Unix.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] More recently a subset of C++ called Embedded C++ has seen some use, for instance it is used in the I/O Kit drivers of macOS.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] Engineers working at Google created Go in 2007 to address developer productivity in large distributed systems, with developer-focused features such as Concurrency, Garbage Collection, and faster program compilation than C and C++.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] In 2015 Rust came out, a general-purpose programming language often used in systems programming.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] Rust was designed with memory safety in mind and to be as performant as C and C++.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] For historical reasons, some organizations use the term *systems programmer* to describe a job function which would be more accurately termed systems administrator.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] This is particularly true in organizations whose computer resources have historically been dominated by mainframes, although the term is even used to describe job functions which do not involve mainframes.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] This usage arose because administration of IBM mainframes often involved the writing of custom assembler code (IBM's Basic Assembly Language (BAL)), which integrated with the operating system such as OS/MVS, DOS/VSE or VM/CMS.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] Indeed, some IBM software products had substantial code contributions from customer programming staff.
[src:d-language/systems-programming] This type of programming is progressively less common, and increasingly done in C rather than Assembly, but the term *systems programmer* is still used as the de-facto job title for staff administering IBM mainframes even in cases where they do not regularly engage in systems programming activities.
[src:d-language/tour-dlang-org] Welcome to the interactive tour of the *D Programming language*.
[src:d-language/tour-dlang-org] The tour gives an overview of this **powerful** and **expressive** language which compiles directly to **efficient**, **native** machine code.
[src:d-language/tour-dlang-org] Each section comes with a source code example that can be modified and used to experiment with D's language features.
[src:d-language/tour-dlang-org] Click the run button (or `Ctrl-enter`) to compile and run it.
[src:d-language/tour-dlang-org] To navigate this tour, either use the "`<` previous" and "next `>`" links at the bottom (or left and right arrow keys), or else go straight to particular sections using the menus at the top.
[src:d-language/tour-dlang-org] This tour is open source and we welcome pull requests making this tour even better.
